ExtraaLearn Project

Context

The EdTech industry has been surging in the past decade immensely, and according to a forecast, the Online Education market would be worth $286.62bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 10.26% from 2018 to 2023. The modern era of online education has enforced a lot in its growth and expansion beyond any limit. Due to having many dominant features like ease of information sharing, personalized learning experience, transparency of assessment, etc, it is now preferable to traditional education.

In the present scenario due to the Covid-19, the online education sector has witnessed rapid growth and is attracting a lot of new customers. Due to this rapid growth, many new companies have emerged in this industry. With the availability and ease of use of digital marketing resources, companies can reach out to a wider audience with their offerings. The customers who show interest in these offerings are termed as leads. There are various sources of obtaining leads for Edtech companies, like

  • The customer interacts with the marketing front on social media or other online platforms.
  • The customer browses the website/app and downloads the brochure
  • The customer connects through emails for more information.

The company then nurtures these leads and tries to convert them to paid customers. For this, the representative from the organization connects with the lead on call or through email to share further details.

Objective

ExtraaLearn is an initial stage startup that offers programs on cutting-edge technologies to students and professionals to help them upskill/reskill. With a large number of leads being generated on a regular basis, one of the issues faced by ExtraaLearn is to identify which of the leads are more likely to convert so that they can allocate resources accordingly. You, as a data scientist at ExtraaLearn, have been provided the leads data to:

  • Analyze and build an ML model to help identify which leads are more likely to convert to paid customers,
  • Find the factors driving the lead conversion process
  • Create a profile of the leads which are likely to convert

Data Description

The data contains the different attributes of leads and their interaction details with ExtraaLearn. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • ID: ID of the lead
  • age: Age of the lead
  • current_occupation: Current occupation of the lead. Values include 'Professional','Unemployed',and 'Student'
  • first_interaction: How did the lead first interacted with ExtraaLearn. Values include 'Website', 'Mobile App'
  • profile_completed: What percentage of profile has been filled by the lead on the website/mobile app. Values include Low - (0-50%), Medium - (50-75%), High (75-100%)
  • website_visits: How many times has a lead visited the website
  • time_spent_on_website: Total time spent on the website
  • page_views_per_visit: Average number of pages on the website viewed during the visits.
  • last_activity: Last interaction between the lead and ExtraaLearn.
    • Email Activity: Seeking for details about program through email, Representative shared information with lead like brochure of program , etc
    • Phone Activity: Had a Phone Conversation with representative, Had conversation over SMS with representative, etc
    • Website Activity: Interacted on live chat with representative, Updated profile on website, etc
  • print_media_type1: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Newspaper.
  • print_media_type2: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Magazine.
  • digital_media: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn on the digital platforms.
  • educational_channels: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn in the education channels like online forums, discussion threads, educational websites, etc.
  • referral: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn through reference.
  • status: Flag indicating whether the lead was converted to a paid customer or not.

# Defining the hist_box() function that plots a boxplot and histogram in one visual. 
def hist_box(df, col):
    f, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': (0.15, 0.85)}, figsize=(12, 6))
    # Adding a graph in each part
    sns.boxplot(data=df, x=col, ax=ax_box, showmeans=True)
    sns.histplot(data=df, x=col, kde=True, ax=ax_hist)
    plt.show()

Bivariate and Multivariate analysis

Next I wantstow check howthe observations of status, our target variable, are relatedtohthe predictor variables Given that the values in the status column are a flag indicating whether the lead was converted to a paid customer or not, we can assume that status 0 = lead not converted and 1 = lead converted. This thinking aligns with the concept of a sales/marketing conversion funnel whereby leads that eventually become paid customers tend to be less than those targeted through marketing efforts. .

Pair plot

I will define a plot function to visualise the relationships percentage-wise using stacked bar plots.

In[1103]:
# Let us plot  for the variables. 
for i in cat_cols:
    if i!='status':
        (pd.crosstab(df[i],df['status'],normalize='index')*100).plot(kind='bar',figsize=(10,4),stacked=True)
        plt.ylabel('Percentage status %')

Observations:

The information we gain about how the variables relate to status includes:

  • The chances of observing conversions by current occupation were; Professionals ~40% followed by unemployed ~30% and students ~10%.

  • The first interaction rates associated with conversion were website ~55% and mobile 45%. Thus website has the highest impact in lead conversion.

  • The rate of profile completion amongst conversions is mainly between High ~40% and Medium ~20, indicating that having the personal details e.g., contact information details about a prospect is positively related to chances of conversion.

  • The chances of observing High, Medium, and Low profile completion rates among converted leads were ~40%, ~20% and ~7% respectively.

  • Chances of conversion were associated mostly with Website activity ~40%, then Email activity ~30% and Phone activity -20%. Website activity is thus the best interaction platform for converting leads.

  • For the print media types, conversions were roughly equally to have seen and not seen the adverts in newspaper and magazine.

  • Similarly, conversions were also roughly equally to have seen and not seen the adverts on digital media platforms, approximately 30%.

  • Echoing what we observed for digital media, the chances of conversions having seen and not seen the ad on educational channels were also similar, approximately 30%.

  • The overall observation regarding communication channels is that neither print media, digital media, nor referrals deliver can be expected to deliver a lead conversion rate above 30%, respectively. This means that a closer investigation effectiveness of media channels is required to justify marketing expenditure and the communication strategy.

# Creating metric function 
def metrics_score(actual, predicted):
    print(classification_report(actual, predicted))

    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f')
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

Model evaluation criterion:

The model can make wrong predictions which may lead to loss of resources or opportunity e.g.:

  1. Predicting a conversion by a lead which does not happen
  2. Predicting a lead will not convert into a paying customer whereas the lead does convert

Which case is more important?

  • Given the business problem our models should ideally predict that customer will be converted given e.g., the resources such as marketing expenditure on several platforms by the company. Thus, higher efforts can be focused on targeting true positives which represent a potential source of income for the company and by implication a return on marketing spend.

How to increase this conversions i.e., improve True Positives?

  • Since we are dealing with imbalanced classes in our dataset, increasing true positives would require a strategy such as maximizing Recall, the greater the Recall, the lesser the chances of false negatives. Experimenting with different approaches therefore allows us to find the best balance between true positives and false positives.

  • True Positive (Actual=1, Predicted=1): Model predicts that a lead would convert and the lead actually converts

Finding the optimal threshold for the model using the Precision-Recall Curve

Precision-Recall curve summarizes the trade-off between the true positive rate and the positive predictive value for a predictive model using different probability thresholds. Thus using the Precision-Recall curve, we can attempt to find a better threshold.

In[1120]:
# Predict_proba gives the probability of each observation belonging to each class
y_scores_lg=lg.predict_proba(X_train_scaled)

precisions_lg, recalls_lg, thresholds_lg = precision_recall_curve(y_train, y_scores_lg[:,1])

# Plot values of precisions, recalls, and thresholds
plt.figure(figsize=(10,7))
plt.plot(thresholds_lg, precisions_lg[:-1], 'b--', label='precision')
plt.plot(thresholds_lg, recalls_lg[:-1], 'g--', label = 'recall')
plt.xlabel('Threshold')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.ylim([0,1])
plt.show()

Observations:

  • We can see that precision and recall are balanced for a threshold of about ~0.45.

Interpretation and Conclusions:

  • The decision tree starts with the feature first interaction on website.

  • The tree proceeds to consider the time the lead spent on the company's website, if the time was greater or equal to 419.50, it considers the features age and last activity on website. If however, the time was greater or equal to 414.00, it considers the features last activity phone profile completed medium. 5

  • The similar process can be used to trace the decisions through to the leaf nodes using e.g., the code **print(tree.export_text(dt, feature_names=X_train.columns.tolist(), show_weights=True)).

Do we need to prune the tree?

  • Since the Decision Tree is overfitting on the training dataset, we would want to reduce this to minimise misclassification.

  • Although pruning the Decision Tree could possibly help with reducing overfitting, it requires more computation to arrive at the rate of error in misclassification and entropy i.e., information loss and is thus costly.

  • Furthermore, another important consideration apart from overfitting, is the quality of the classifier. The performance of the Decision Tree on the test set reveals that using all the features, the classifier will be 65% correct in predicting that a lead will be converted. The recall score indicates 64% of the conversions were predicted correctly. Considering the f1-score which is defined as the Harmonic Mean of the Precision and Recall, we can conclude that the Decision tree classifier has a 64% chance of being correct and not miss any correct predictions.

  • Therefore instead of pruning, alternatives to pruning in order to improve the model performance and tackle overfitting include tuning the Decision Tree's hyperpameters or employing ensemble methods which are trained on different subsets of the dataset.

Motivation for tuning the hyperparemeters using GridSearch CV:

  • The reason behind tuning is to see if the model performance will be improved by adjusting hyperparameters

  • The algorithm finds the optimal values for the hyperparameters (e.g., tree depth, minimum samples) increasing the generalization and preventing overfitting.

Checking the performance of the model on the train and test data using the tuned model

In[1144]:
# Choosing the type of classifier
dtree_estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight='balanced', random_state=1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {'max_depth': np.arange(2, 7), 
              'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
              'min_samples_leaf': [5, 10, 20, 25]
             }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
import sklearn.metrics as metrics
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label = 1)

# Run the grid search
gridCV = GridSearchCV(dtree_estimator, parameters, scoring = scorer, cv = 10)

# Fitting the grid search on the train data
gridCV = gridCV.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the classifier to the best combination of parameters
dtree_estimator = gridCV.best_estimator_

# Fit the best estimator to the data
dtree_estimator.fit(X_train, y_train)

Model performance and selection

  • Having built multiple models and checked their performance using the recall and precision scores, we identified that the best model should reduce overfitting and be able to predict correctly and not miss any correct predictions, at the highest level possible.

  • The F1-score represents a compromise between Precision and Recall therefore it is a reliable measure of the quality of the classifier.

  • The summary table shows that on the test dataset, the tuned Decision Tree and the Random Forest before and after tuning had the highest F1-score 0.76. Thus we should select the Random Forest model as our final model.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations

  • In this anaysis, we were able to identify the key factors that are associated with leads eventually converting to paying customers of Extraalearn.

  • Our final model based on the Random Forest regressor showed that the important features which influence conversion are mainly the level of interaction the leads have with the company, particularly on the website.

  • Therefore the company's digital marketing efforts must focus on:

    • making an impactful first impression on leads when they visit the website for the first time
    • publishing website content that is engaging and relevant
    • ensuring a friendly user-experience
    • adding consenting leads to periodic newsletters that have a link to the website
    • paying attention to leads with medium complete profiles by for instance notifying them that their profiles are incomplete as a prompt to logon to the website and finish the process

Such initiaves would help increase the rate of website visits, page views per visit and make time spent on website by leads worthwhile in their information-gathering and decision-making processes.

  • We observed that age is also an important determining factor in conversion. With the average lead being 46 years of age, the company's market segmentation strategy would need to be reviewed to check if it aligns with this insight. Employing methods such as clustering would further assist with understanding the age demographic of leads and drivers of conversion.

  • The company must allocate resources for personal interaction or one-to-one communication with leads given the importance of the last activity phone feature.

  • Lastly, the needs of leads who are unemployed or students must be considered and accomodated in order to increase their probability to convert. E.g., offering more personal support such as guidance prior to registration and financial assistance.
